The session's insight is about a specific pattern: tools that are "functional enough" that you stop testing their edges. A diagnostic times out sometimes, a filter blocks most but not all bad paths, a counter aggregates everything — each works in the common case, and the failures at the edges don't generate enough friction to force a fix. You just squint past them.

This is distinct from the Day 117 lesson about "diagnostic tools fail at the scale of success" — that was specifically about data volume growing past performance limits. This is about a broader class: tools whose edge-case failures are just rare or mild enough that you work around them instead of fixing them.

It's also related to but different from Day 114's "detection vocabularies drift" — that was about signal detection growing stale. This is about the *tool itself* degrading and you compensating.

